   <question id="q1">
      <body>
         <p>Find P(D1) and
               P(D2).<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T131835-0500"?> Write
               your answers in the text box below.<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
      </body>
      <short_answer id="A"/>
      <part>
         <response input="A" match="*" score="1"/>
         <explanation>
            <p>To be a potential donor for patient 1, who has blood type A, a person must
                  have<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T131934-0500" content=" either"?>
                  blood type A or O. Therefore:</p>
            <p>P(D1) = P(A or O) = P(A) + P(O) = .42 + .44 = .86. </p>
            <p>Note that in this case we can safely use the addition rule for disjoint events since
                  the events A and O are disjoint because
                  <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T132333-0500"?>we are
                  presuming that <?oxy_insert_end?>a person cannot have more than one blood
                  type.</p>
            <p>Similarly, to be a potential donor for patient 2, who has blood type B, a person must
                  have<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T132354-0500" content=" either"?>
                  blood type B or O. Therefore:</p>
            <p>P(D2) = P(B) + P(O) = .10 + .44 = .54.</p>
         </explanation>
      </part>
   </question></page>
